Coronavirus: stay up to date
See coronavirus travel advice for guidance on travel during the COVID-19 pandemic.
Sign up for email alerts for Grenada travel advice.
The first coronavirus (COVID 19) case in Grenada was confirmed on 22 March. From 23 March, Grenada’s airports will close to commercial flights but some flights to and from the UK are still running. See @UkinCaribbean for details. If you were booked on these flights you are advised to contact the airlines for the latest information. See Health
If you wish to leave the country, contact your airline or travel company and your insurance provider as soon as you are able, and keep up to date with the latest developments. International travel may become more difficult
The Government of Grenada announced that, effective from 19 March, until further notice, any non-Grenadian nationals and non-residents arriving in Grenada with a travel history in the UK and the rest of Europe within the last 14 days will not be permitted entry into Grenada. From the 22 March this also applies to travellers with a recent travel history to the US. This follows similar restrictions for persons with a travel history in mainland China, Italy, Iran, South Korea and Germany, France and Spain, within the last 14 days. Effective from 16 March, disembarkation from cruise vessels will also not be permitted in Grenada. Effective 22 March, non-Grenadian passengers and crew on yachts will not be permitted to disembark in Grenada, Carriacou, and Petite Martinique. Any failure to comply will result in a fine or detention.
The hurricane season in Grenada normally runs from June to November. You should monitor local and international weather updates from the US National Hurricane Center and follow the advice of local authorities, including any evacuation orders. See Natural disasters
UK health authorities have classified Grenada as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For more information and advice, visit the National Travel Health Network and Centre website.
Cases of Chikungunya virus have been confirmed in Grenada. You should take steps to avoid being bitten by mosquitoes.
Most visits to Grenada are trouble-free but there have been incidents of crime including armed robbery and sexual assault. See Crime
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in Grenada, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
Consular support may be limited in Grenada as there is no British High Commission office. However, the British High Commission in Bridgetown, Barbados, can provide consular support.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
